# 40_objects_set_stroke_miter_opacity — closes the appearance
# branch's remaining stroke axis (miter and opacity).
#
# s240 m1 shipped the enum-token sub-axis (cap and join). s241
# m1 closes the remaining two numeric stroke fields. Both reuse
# arg_as_double from s239 m2 — no new helper, no new command,
# near-mechanical given the established pattern.
#
# After this milestone, all six StrokeStyle fields are
# addressable from scripts:
#   - paint  (s239 m1, set_stroke + stroke query)
#   - width  (s239 m2, set_stroke_width + stroke_width query)
#   - cap    (s240 m1, set_stroke_cap + cap query)
#   - join   (s240 m1, set_stroke_join + join query)
#   - miter  (s241 m1, set_stroke_miter + miter query — THIS)
#   - opacity(s241 m1, set_stroke_opacity + stroke_opacity query
#                                                  — THIS)
#
# Plus the fill axis from s238 m1. The appearance branch is now
# fully closed for direct-paint surfaces. Remaining backlog:
# gradient tokens, swatch bindings, mutate_appearance alignment
# decision.
#
# Material differences from set_stroke_width (m2):
#   - Field names. set_stroke_miter writes to
#     SceneNode::stroke.miter; set_stroke_opacity writes to
#     SceneNode::stroke.opacity. Both are doubles.
#   - Naming divergence noted (backlog item):
#     SceneNode::stroke.miter (4.0 default) vs
#     style::Style::stroke.miter_limit (4.0 default) are the
#     same concept under different field names on two different
#     structs. ObjectsScriptable surfaces the verb as
#     set_stroke_miter (matches SceneNode); StylesScriptable
#     surfaces its setter as stroke_miter_limit (matches
#     style::Style). Whether to align the field names is open.
#   - Query naming: `miter` (drops stroke_ prefix; the proxy IS
#     the object, no surface ambiguity) and `stroke_opacity`
#     (keeps stroke_ prefix to disambiguate from layer-level
#     opacity meanings that LayersProxy uses).
#   - Same partial binding-clear convention: clear bound_style,
#     preserve fill_swatch_id and stroke_swatch_id (these edits
#     don't touch paint).
#   - No clamp / no negative-refusal. Same convention as
#     set_stroke_width. Negative opacity zeros at Cairo's clamp;
#     opacity > 1.0 saturates at 1.0; negative miter is honoured
#     by the model but the renderer treats it as 0.0 (clip
#     immediately).
#
# Verify-before-assume's NINTH and TENTH "fits unmodified" cases
# in a row. EditAppearanceCommand's whole-StrokeStyle capture
# covers miter and opacity along with everything else without
# modification.
#
# ── Owns-its-conditions structure (CANON) ────────────────────────────────
#
# BUILD UP / VALIDATE / TEAR DOWN. The smoke mints its own test
# layer and three test objects (a Path `p` for the numeric
# matrix, a Group `g` for the universal-class probe, a second
# Path `v` for the visual-close phase), validates the new
# surface end-to-end, and tears everything back down.
#
# ── Pre-stated count ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Expected: 16 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#
# Breakdown:
#   Phase 1 (REGISTRY):                                       → 0 asserts.
#   Phase 2 (DISPATCH — baseline count):                      → 0 asserts.
#   Phase 3 (BUILD UP — mint test_layer, Path `p`, geometry,
#            baseline miter and opacity defaults):
#     p type == "path",
#     p miter == 4.0 (StrokeStyle struct default),
#     p stroke_opacity == 1.0 (StrokeStyle struct default)     → 3 asserts.
#   Phase 4 (SET miter — Double literal):
#     p miter == 8.0                                           → 1 assert.
#   Phase 5 (SET miter — Int coerces via arg_as_double):
#     p miter == 2.0                                           → 1 assert.
#   Phase 6 (SET stroke_opacity — half-transparent):
#     p stroke_opacity == 0.5                                  → 1 assert.
#   Phase 7 (SET stroke_opacity — fully transparent gesture):
#     p stroke_opacity == 0.0                                  → 1 assert.
#   Phase 8 (NEGATIVE-VALUE-ACCEPTED — model honest, no clamp;
#            opacity == -0.5 lands on model, renderer clamps
#            at Cairo seam):
#     p stroke_opacity == -0.5                                 → 1 assert.
#   Phase 9 (UNIVERSAL — miter and opacity on a Group):
#     g type == "group",
#     g miter == 10.0,
#     g stroke_opacity == 0.75                                 → 3 asserts.
#   Phase 10 (VISUAL CLOSE — hairpin polygon with miter join,
#             miter limit high enough to extend the point,
#             stroke_opacity 0.5 so fill shows through stroke):
#     v stroke_width == 40.0,
#     v miter == 100.0,
#     v stroke_opacity == 0.5                                  → 3 asserts.
#   Phase 11 (CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type "path" still resolves):
#     found_path type == "path"                                → 1 assert.
#   Phase 12 (TEAR DOWN — round-trip count):
#     objects count == count_before                            → 1 assert.
#
# Total: 0 + 0 + 3 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 3 + 3 + 1 + 1 = 16.
#
# ── On the negative-opacity Phase 8 ──────────────────────────────────────
#
# The model accepts negative opacity; the renderer clamps at the
# Cairo seam (cairo_set_source_rgba's alpha is conceptually
# 0.0-1.0, and a negative alpha renders as fully transparent).
# So `set_stroke_opacity -0.5` lands -0.5 on the model, the
# query reads it back as -0.5, but the canvas renders no
# outline. Same "model accepts whatever; renderer handles edge
# cases" convention StylesScriptable / set_stroke_width follow.
#
# Whether to add a 0.0-1.0 clamp at the script surface is a
# backlog item; consistency with the rest of the appearance arc
# wins for now. Same posture as set_stroke_width's negative-
# width Phase 7 in smoke 38.
#
# ── On the visual-close Phase 10 ─────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The miter-and-opacity payoff phase. Mint a second Path `v`,
# set its geometry to a HAIRPIN polygon — three points forming
# a sharp acute angle where miter extension would be dramatic.
# Layer the appearance values:
#   - fill = "yellow" (opaque interior so opacity's effect on
#     stroke vs fill is visible).
#   - stroke = "blue" (the outline colour).
#   - stroke_width = 40.0 (fat enough for miter / opacity
#     effects to read at default zoom).
#   - stroke_cap = "round" (cleans up the open endpoints; not
#     the focus of this milestone but avoids visual clutter
#     from default butt caps on the hairpin's open ends).
#   - stroke_join = "miter" (REQUIRED for miter to have any
#     visible effect; bevel and round joins ignore miter).
#   - miter = 100.0 (very high — extends the corner point well
#     beyond what default 4.0 would allow on a sharp angle).
#   - stroke_opacity = 0.5 (the YELLOW fill shows through the
#     half-transparent BLUE stroke at the overlap; the visible
#     stroke colour is the blend of blue-and-yellow,
#     approximately gray-green, in the overlap region. Where
#     the stroke extends past the fill (the miter point), it
#     reads as half-transparent blue against the canvas
#     background).
#
# The trace asserts the three new fields independently; the
# VISUAL channel — Scott looking at the canvas — shows a
# hairpin shape with a long sharp miter point at the acute
# corner, half-transparent blue outline, fill showing through.
#
# Three-channel acceptance for s241 m1 = trace pass (16 asserts)
# + clean build + VISIBLE miter extension and half-transparent
# stroke after Phase 10.
#
# ── Canvas-observable (three-channel acceptance) ─────────────────────────
#
# Trace channel: the 16 asserts above.
# Visual channel: AFTER Phase 10, the document shows a hairpin
#   polygon at user-origin (300, 0) — three points forming a
#   sharp acute angle — with a yellow fill, half-transparent
#   blue 40px stroke, round caps, miter join, and a clearly
#   extended miter point at the acute corner. The colour at the
#   overlap reads as a blue-yellow blend; the miter extension
#   pokes well past the corner geometry.
# Build channel: Scott's compile.

#[sub] === Phase 1: REGISTRY ===
#[sub] `objects` should appear in the registry list — baseline.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: DISPATCH — baseline count ===
#[sub] Captures the pre-mint object count to compare against after
#[sub] teardown.

get objects count
set count_before to result

#[sub] === Phase 3: BUILD UP — mint test layer, Path, geometry ===
#[sub] Mint a sentinel-named test layer, activate it, mint `p` as a
#[sub] Path, set its geometry. A freshly-minted Path has
#[sub] stroke.miter defaulting to 4.0 and stroke.opacity defaulting
#[sub] to 1.0 (SceneNode.hpp:78-79 struct defaults).

layers new
set test_layer to result
layers.test_layer rename "objects_set_stroke_miter_opacity_smoke_s241_m1"
layers.test_layer activate

objects new "path"
set p to result
objects.p set_path_data "M 0 0 L 100 0 L 100 100 L 0 100 Z"

assert objects.p type == "path"
assert objects.p miter == 4.0
assert objects.p stroke_opacity == 1.0

#[sub] === Phase 4: SET miter — Double literal byte-clean ===
#[sub] Double-kind literal `8.0` lands directly on stroke.miter
#[sub] via arg_as_double's native-Double branch. Query reads it
#[sub] back through ScriptValue::real; assert's RHS is also a
#[sub] Double literal so the strict-kind equality compares
#[sub] value-on-value.

objects.p set_stroke_miter 8.0
assert objects.p miter == 8.0

#[sub] === Phase 5: SET miter — Int coerces to Double via arg_as_double ===
#[sub] Int-kind literal `2` goes through arg_as_double's
#[sub] static_cast<double> branch and lands stroke.miter = 2.0.
#[sub] The query returns Double(2.0); the assert RHS is `2.0`
#[sub] (Double), so the kind-strict equality matches. Same
#[sub] coercion path that smoke 38 exercises on stroke_width.

objects.p set_stroke_miter 2
assert objects.p miter == 2.0

#[sub] === Phase 6: SET stroke_opacity — half-transparent ===
#[sub] Double literal 0.5 lands on stroke.opacity. The model
#[sub] field is a 0.0-1.0 alpha multiplier applied to the
#[sub] resolved stroke paint at the Cairo seam. Visual effect
#[sub] is half-strength outline; not visible on a fresh path
#[sub] with zero stroke width yet, but the model state is
#[sub] correct (Phase 10 makes it visible with a fat stroke).

objects.p set_stroke_opacity 0.5
assert objects.p stroke_opacity == 0.5

#[sub] === Phase 7: SET stroke_opacity — fully transparent gesture ===
#[sub] Explicit 0.0 is the "no outline" gesture distinct from
#[sub] the fresh-mint default (which arrives at 1.0). At
#[sub] opacity=0.0 the renderer composites the resolved stroke
#[sub] paint at zero alpha — no outline visible. Different from
#[sub] stroke_width=0.0 (which short-circuits the stroke pass
#[sub] entirely) but visually equivalent.

objects.p set_stroke_opacity 0.0
assert objects.p stroke_opacity == 0.0

#[sub] === Phase 8: NEGATIVE-VALUE-ACCEPTED ===
#[sub] The model accepts negative opacity; the renderer clamps
#[sub] at the Cairo seam. Trace channel shows -0.5; visual
#[sub] channel renders no outline (same as Phase 7's zero). This
#[sub] matches StylesScriptable / set_stroke_width's "model
#[sub] accepts whatever; renderer handles edge cases" convention.

objects.p set_stroke_opacity -0.5
assert objects.p stroke_opacity == -0.5

#[sub] === Phase 9: UNIVERSAL — miter and opacity on a Group ===
#[sub] Same universal posture as every other appearance verb.
#[sub] Appearance lives on every SceneNode subtype.

objects new "group"
set g to result
objects.g set_stroke_miter 10.0
objects.g set_stroke_opacity 0.75

assert objects.g type == "group"
assert objects.g miter == 10.0
assert objects.g stroke_opacity == 0.75

#[sub] === Phase 10: VISUAL CLOSE ===
#[sub] The appearance branch's full-closure payoff. Mint a
#[sub] second Path `v` with a HAIRPIN polygon (three points
#[sub] forming a sharp acute angle where miter extension is
#[sub] dramatic). Layer the appearance values:
#[sub]   - fill = "yellow" (opaque interior).
#[sub]   - stroke = "blue" (outline).
#[sub]   - stroke_width = 40.0 (fat enough for both miter and
#[sub]     opacity effects to register).
#[sub]   - stroke_cap = "round" (cleans up the hairpin's open
#[sub]     endpoints).
#[sub]   - stroke_join = "miter" (REQUIRED for miter limit to
#[sub]     have any visible effect).
#[sub]   - miter = 100.0 (extends the corner point well past
#[sub]     default 4.0 on the acute angle).
#[sub]   - stroke_opacity = 0.5 (yellow fill shows through the
#[sub]     half-transparent blue stroke).
#[sub] The hairpin path: starts at (300, 200), goes up to a
#[sub] sharp point at (350, 0), comes back down to (400, 200).
#[sub] The acute angle at (350, 0) gets the dramatic miter
#[sub] extension.

objects new "path"
set v to result
objects.v set_path_data "M 300 200 L 350 0 L 400 200"
objects.v set_fill "yellow"
objects.v set_stroke "blue"
objects.v set_stroke_width 40.0
objects.v set_stroke_cap "round"
objects.v set_stroke_join "miter"
objects.v set_stroke_miter 100.0
objects.v set_stroke_opacity 0.5

assert objects.v stroke_width == 40.0
assert objects.v miter == 100.0
assert objects.v stroke_opacity == 0.5

#[sub] === Phase 11: CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type "path" still resolves ===
#[sub] Sanity check that the appearance work didn't disturb the
#[sub] iid index. `p` and `v` are both Paths; first-hit returns
#[sub] one of them.

objects find_by_type "path"
set found_path to result
assert objects.found_path type == "path"

#[sub] === Phase 12: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Four mints (test_layer, p, g, v) — four matching deletes.
#[sub] count returns to count_before — round-trip baseline.

objects delete p
objects delete g
objects delete v
layers delete test_layer

get objects count
assert objects count == count_before

#[sub] === Final list — registry sanity ===
#[sub] `objects` still present; no transient proxies registered.

list

#[sub] Done. The s241 m1 surface is validated:
#[sub]   - `objects.<iid> set_stroke_miter <number>` accepts
#[sub]     Double and Int (Int coerced via arg_as_double),
#[sub]     writes directly onto SceneNode::stroke.miter, clears
#[sub]     bound_style, preserves both swatch ids.
#[sub]   - `objects.<iid> set_stroke_opacity <number>` same
#[sub]     shape on SceneNode::stroke.opacity.
#[sub]   - `miter` query returns the double directly via
#[sub]     ScriptValue::real. Default 4.0.
#[sub]   - `stroke_opacity` query same shape. Default 1.0.
#[sub]   - No clamp, no negative-refusal — matches set_stroke_width.
#[sub]   - Universal across SceneNode subtypes.
#[sub]   - The canvas-observable arc's appearance branch is now
#[sub]     CLOSED on all six StrokeStyle fields plus the fill
#[sub]     axis. Six fields addressable; remaining work is
#[sub]     gradient and swatch bindings.
#[sub]
#[sub] Pre-stated: 16 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#[sub]
#[sub] What's still NOT covered (backlog):
#[sub]   - Gradient tokens on fill or stroke. Same scope-limit
#[sub]     as s238 / s239 / s240.
#[sub]   - Swatch / style binding via script.
#[sub]   - mutate_appearance alignment decision.
#[sub]   - cap_to_string / decode_cap / join_to_string /
#[sub]     decode_join pump-pair promotion to curvz_utils (two
#[sub]     callers, third would justify lift).
#[sub]   - SceneNode::stroke.miter vs style::Style::stroke.miter_limit
#[sub]     field-name alignment. Backlog item this session.
#[sub]   - Undo / redo exercise.
